{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d135481a-7019-48b4-816f-1787e9c8095d","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test ID computation**. The fully-qualified ID now includes more information (namespace + class + method), so Azure DevOps sees every test as brand new. You can restore the legacy IDs by adding to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr accept the one-time history break and move forward with the new IDs.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — no test is running yet, so `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it coincidentally returned the first test's name (unreliable). Your fix on line 13:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead, or\n    // move test-specific logic into [TestInitialize]\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallelism** | Class-level parallelism is now the default; add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or disable if tests aren't thread-safe |\n| **Assert.ThrowsException** | Now also catches derived exception types (was exact-match only in v3) |\n| **TestContext.Properties** | Read-only in fixture contexts; writing throws |\n| **DataRow display names** | Default format changed → may affect test filters/selectors |\n| **Timeout attribute** | Now applies to setup/cleanup too, not just the test body |\n\nThe most impactful for your code is the `ClassInitialize` issue. Would you like me to refactor `SetupTests.cs` to be v4-compatible?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"797bad52-780f-46ba-afa0-00275880ce0c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide guidance based on what I know about MSTest v4 changes:\n\n1. **Test ID changes (lost history in Azure DevOps)**: MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed. In v3, the fully qualified test ID used the test method name only. In v4, the default test ID includes additional information (like the fully qualified class name), which causes Azure DevOps to see them as entirely new tests. There's a way to opt back into the legacy ID generation.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a class-level context, not tied to any specific test method. Accessing `TestName` on it now throws an `InvalidOperationException` because there's no test running yet at class initialization time. \n\nIn v3 it would unreliably return the name of whichever test happened to trigger the initialization first. Beyond that, there are several other areas to be aware of: the `[AssemblyInitialize]` context also lacks test-specific properties, `DeploymentItem` behavior has shifted, `DataRow` attributes handle display names differently, parallelism defaults may have changed, and `TestContext.Properties` is read-only in certain scenarios.","outputTokens":859,"requestId":"843C:729EF:22670BE:25F3074:6A0AD798"},"id":"09377574-153a-43a2-85e4-8b385c2ffe9e","timestamp":"2026-05-18T09:11:07.941Z","parentId":"32064d92-267e-4848-ae63-24a88ce06543"}
